        <h2 class="w3-wide">ABOUT AIR POLLUTION</h2>
        <p class="w3-opacity"><i>What is it?</i></p>
        <p class="w3-justify">

            Air pollution is basically the release of pollutants into the air that are deadly to the human health as well as the planet as a whole. A common
            link to air pollution is Global Warming. As we heat the Earth, the ice caps melt and thus, in turn, the sea level rises.

        <p class="w3-opacity"><i>What are the common causes?</i></p>

        Arguably the main cause of air pollution is the burning of fossil fuels. Burning these fossil fuels, that took millions of years to form mind you, is releasing
        gases and chemicals into the air, our atmosphere. these gases are not only contributing to the climate change we are fearing right now, but it seems to be
        exacerbated by it.
        <br> <br>
        Where do you think the smog comes from? as this pollution heats up the Earth's temperature in the form of methane and carbon dioxide, other forms of air pollution
        are worsened, resulting in smog forming, as well as the increase of mold being noticed around, due to the dampness increase to areas near the water, be it sea or lake.
        increases in flooding occur, as mentioned before, due to the rise in sea levels.
        <br> <br>
        All in all, due to our need for the power amount these fossil fuels provide, this need seems to be shaping our future into a much more darker one. These fossil fuels are running out
        rapidly, resulting in their higher costs such as gas pumps for cars in need etc. However, with their increase in usage, we are harming the Earth's atmosphere, and harming ourselves
        in the process. For more details on the effects of air pollution, continue reading and see how it is harming both us and our planet.

        <br> <br>


        <h2 class="w3-wide">EFFECTS OF AIR POLLUTION</h2>
        <table style="width:100%">
            <p class="w3-opacity"><i>Smog and Soot</i></p>
            These two are the most prevalent types of air pollution. Smog, or “ground-level ozone” as it better known, is made when emissions from the combustion of fossil fuels with sunlight.
            Soot, also known as “particulate matter,” is made up of tiny particles of chemicals, soil, smoke, dust, or allergens, in the form of gas or solids, and is carried in the air.
            The sources of smog and soot are similar. Both come from cars and trucks, factories, power plants, incinerators, engines—anything that combusts fossil fuels such as coal, gas,
            or natural gas. Soot is dangerous as the tiniest airborne particles within it—whether they’re in the form of gas or solids—can penetrate the lungs and
            bloodstream and worsen bronchitis and lead to heart attacks.

            <p class="w3-opacity"><i>Greenhouse Gas</i></p>
            By trapping the earth’s heat in the atmosphere, greenhouse gases lead to warmer temperatures and all the hallmarks of climate change: rising sea levels, more extreme weather,
            heat-related deaths, and increasing transmission of infectious diseases like Lyme.Studies have shown that carbon dioxide was responsible for 81 percent of the NA total
            greenhouse gas emissions, and methane made up 11 percent. “Carbon dioxide comes from combusting fossil fuels, and methane comes from natural and industrial sources.
            Believe it or not but cows are a leading cause of methane. As the meat eaters' demand for beef rises, so does the needed number of cattle, which can only lead to more methane being produced.
            Furthermore, methane is produced by other ways,including the large amounts that are released during oil and gas drilling.According to recent statistics, We emit far larger amounts of carbon dioxide ,
            but methane is significantly more potent, so it’s also very destructive.

            <p class="w3-opacity"><i>Hazardous air pollutants</i></p>

            Lead,mercury, dioxins, and benzene.These are some of the most often emitted during gas and or coal combustion, incinerating, or in the case of benzene, found in gasoline.
            Benzene, can cause eye, skin, and lung irritation in the short term and blood disorders in the long term.
            Dioxins, more typically found in food but also present in small amounts in the air, can affect the liver in the short term and harm the immune, nervous, and endocrine systems,
            as well as reproductive functions.
            Lead in large amounts can damage children’s brains and kidneys, and even in small amounts it can affect children’s IQ and ability to learn.
            Mercury affects the central nervous system.
            Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, or PAHs, are toxic components of traffic exhaust and wildfire smoke. In large amounts,
            they have been linked to eye and lung irritation, blood and liver issues, and even cancer. In one recent study, the children
            of mothers who’d had higher PAH exposure during pregnancy had slower brain processing speeds and worse symptoms of ADHD

            <br> <br>

            Below are some common examples of pollutants and how they threaten our health when in high numbers:

